I am trying to differentiate $2^x$ from first principles. This is what I have so far: \begin{align}
f'(x) &= \underset{h\rightarrow 0}{\textrm{lim}} \frac{f(x+h) - f(x)}{h}\\
\implies \frac{d2^x}{dx} &= \underset{h\rightarrow 0}{\textrm{lim}}\frac{2^{x+h}-2^x}{h}\\
&= \underset{h\rightarrow 0}{\textrm{lim}}\frac{2^x(2^h -1)}{h}
\end{align} From that point on, as the limit is of type 0/0, I was thinking of using L'Hôpital's rule, but this gives
\begin{equation}
\frac{d2^x}{dx} = 2^x\frac{d2^h}{dh}\bigg\rvert_{h=0}.
\end{equation} Not sure how to go from there.

Let $Z$ be a continuous random variable with probability density function: $$
f_Z(z) =  \begin{cases}
\gamma(1 + z^2) & \mbox{ if } -2 < z < 1, \\
0 & \mbox{ otherwise}
\end{cases}
$$ a) For what $γ$ is this possible? b) Find the cumulative distribution function of $Z$.

